    <h2 id="day">A day heliskiing in Iceland, hour by hour</h2>
    <p>A typical day begins with a relaxed breakfast at <a href="/siglo-hotel">Sigló Hótel</a> while the guides study the overnight weather and avalanche data. Mid-morning, once the light and wind are right, the group gears up, receives the safety briefing, and the helicopter lifts off — often from the edge of town. The first drop puts you on a summit or high ridge; you ski a long descent with your guide reading the terrain ahead, and the helicopter meets you at the bottom. Runs stack up through the day — powder laps at altitude early, sun-softened corn on the aspects that have warmed. A mountain lunch is taken in the field. On the best days, guests keep skiing into the long Arctic evening, finishing with 15,000–25,000 vertical feet in the legs before a soak in the harbour hot tubs and a three-course dinner. No two days are identical, because the guides chase the best snow the day offers.</p>

    <h2 id="snow">Powder or corn: choosing your snow</h2>
    <p>Iceland gives you two distinct kinds of skiing depending on when you come. <strong>Powder</strong> dominates the early season (March into April), when cold Arctic storms lay down light, dry snow, best found high up and on north-facing slopes. <strong>Corn snow</strong> takes over in the late season (May–June): as spring sun cycles the snowpack, it refreezes overnight and softens by day into a smooth, forgiving, almost buttery surface that many experienced skiers prefer above all else. Corn is also more predictable and forgiving, which makes late season a strong choice for a first heliski trip. Come early to chase powder and aurora; come late for reliable corn under the midnight sun.</p>

    <h2 id="firsttimer">Heliskiing for first-timers</h2>
    <p>If this is your first helicopter trip, Iceland is a forgiving place to start. You do not need previous heliski or backcountry experience — only solid off-piste skiing and a willingness to follow your guide. The guides brief you thoroughly on helicopter procedure (how to load, where to look, how to handle your skis near the machine) and on avalanche safety before you ski. Terrain is chosen for the group, so a first-timer is never pushed onto lines beyond their level. The late-season corn window, with its softer, more predictable snow and endless daylight, is the gentlest introduction. Come reasonably fit, bring your own boots, and the rest is guided.</p>

    <h2 id="board">Snowboarding and splitboarding in Iceland</h2>
    <p>Iceland heliskiing is fully open to snowboarders — the K2 fleet includes freeride boards such as the Alchemist and Passport, and the open, rolling Troll Peninsula terrain suits a board beautifully, with long fall-line descents and few flat traverses. Splitboarders are welcome too; the <a href="/heli-assisted-touring">Heli-Assisted Touring</a> package pairs helicopter access with earned turns for those who want to combine both. As with skiing, bring your own boots for the best fit and let the guides match the board to the day's snow.</p>

    <h2 id="private">Private vs shared helicopter</h2>
    <p>Most guests fly on a shared basis — the classic model, where two or three small groups share a helicopter and rotate through runs, keeping the cost down while everyone skis plenty. If you want the helicopter to yourself, a <a href="/private-heliskiing">private booking</a> gives your group exclusive use: no waiting on other groups, complete control over pace and terrain, and the flexibility to chase exactly the lines and snow you want. Private weeks suit families, groups of friends of similar ability, or anyone wanting the most bespoke possible trip. Semi-private options sit in between. All three are priced by guaranteed vertical, and we can help you weigh which fits your group on the <a href="/packages">packages</a> page.</p>

    <h2 id="weather">How weather shapes your week</h2>
    <p>Iceland's Arctic weather is part of the adventure, and the vertical-feet model exists precisely so that weather never costs you skiing you have paid for. Some days are bluebird; others bring wind or low cloud that grounds the helicopter for a time. On those days the guides adapt — repositioning to sheltered terrain, waiting out a squall, or switching to ski touring from the valley until the sky clears. Because you are guaranteed vertical rather than flight hours, a weather delay simply moves your skiing, it does not delete it. Building a few days into your trip, rather than a single day, greatly increases your chances of ideal conditions — which is why our <a href="/packages">packages</a> are built around 3, 4 and 5-day weeks.</p>

    <h2 id="fitness">Fitness and how to prepare</h2>
    <p>You do not need to be an athlete, but arriving fit makes the difference between skiing eight runs and skiing fourteen. The helicopter removes the climbing, so the demand is on your legs during long descents and on general endurance across a full day. In the weeks before your trip, focus on leg strength (squats, lunges, step-ups), some cardiovascular base (cycling, running or hiking), and core stability. If you can, get days on snow beforehand to sharpen your off-piste technique — powder and variable snow ask more of you than groomers. Good general condition is enough for a wonderful week; better condition simply means more vertical.</p>

    <h2 id="packing">The full packing checklist</h2>
    <p>Skis or a snowboard, avalanche safety equipment (transceiver, shovel, probe, airbag) and outerwear can all be provided, so most guests pack light. Bring the personal items that must fit you: your own <strong>ski or snowboard boots</strong> and a <strong>helmet</strong> above all. Add warm mid-layers and a base layer system, quality waterproof gloves plus a spare pair, a neck gaiter or buff, quality <strong>sunglasses and ski goggles</strong> (both — for bright and flat light), and high-SPF sun cream and lip balm, because the Arctic spring sun reflecting off snow is stronger than it feels. Pack casual warm clothing for the hotel and hot tubs, swimwear, and any personal medication. A small backpack for the mountain, a camera or phone in a warm pocket, and a good book for any weather day complete the list.</p>

    <h2 id="insurance">Travel insurance and cancellation</h2>
    <p>Comprehensive travel insurance is strongly recommended for any heliski trip, and should cover off-piste and helicopter-accessed skiing specifically — many standard policies exclude it. Look for cover that includes trip cancellation and interruption, lost or delayed equipment, and emergency medical and mountain-rescue evacuation. Global Rescue is a well-regarded specialist provider for exactly this kind of trip. When you book with us we will confirm the operator's terms and the sensible cover to arrange, so nothing is left to chance.</p>

    <h2 id="calendar">Dates and availability</h2>
    <p>The season runs from early March to mid-June, and the best weeks book well ahead — often a year in advance for peak windows. As a rough guide: <strong>March</strong> and <strong>early April</strong> for the most wintry powder and the best Northern Lights; <strong>late April</strong> and <strong>May</strong> for a balance of powder and spring snow; and <strong>late May</strong> into <strong>June</strong> for the most reliable corn skiing under the midnight sun. If you have flexibility, tell us your ideal window and we will find the strongest available week for your group — the earlier you enquire, the more choice you have.</p>

    <h2 id="glossary">A short heliski glossary</h2>
    <p><strong>Vertical feet / vertical:</strong> the total descent skied, and the unit trips are sold in. <strong>Corn snow:</strong> spring snow that refreezes overnight and softens by day into a smooth surface. <strong>IFMGA/UIAGM:</strong> the highest international mountain-guide certification. <strong>Transceiver (beacon):</strong> the avalanche rescue device every guest wears. <strong>Airbag pack:</strong> a backpack that inflates to help keep a skier on the surface in a slide. <strong>Sea-to-summit:</strong> a descent that runs from a snow-covered peak down to the coastline — an Icelandic signature. <strong>Bluebird:</strong> a clear, sunny day. <strong>Skin / touring:</strong> climbing under your own power with grippy skins, offered on heli-assisted days.</p>

    <h2 id="best-world">Where does Iceland rank among the best heliskiing in the world?</h2>
    <p>When skiers ask where the best heliskiing in the world is, the same handful of regions always appear: British Columbia in Canada, Alaska, Japan's Hokkaido, the European Alps, Kamchatka in Russia — and, increasingly, Iceland. Each earns its place for a different reason, and Iceland has risen fast because it offers something none of the others can: mountains that rise straight from the Arctic Ocean, giving descents that run from snow-covered summits all the way to the sea. Add the midnight sun, the Northern Lights, one of the longest seasons in the sport (March to mid-June), and a four-star hotel at the base rather than a remote camp, and Iceland has become a fixture on every serious heliskier's list. For a first heliski trip in particular — accessible terrain, forgiving spring corn, short flights from base — many guides now rate the Tröllaskagi Peninsula as the finest introduction to the sport anywhere.</p>

    <h2 id="zones">The eleven heliski zones of the Troll Peninsula</h2>
    <p>Viking Heliskiing's home terrain on the Tröllaskagi Peninsula is divided into eleven mapped heliskiing zones, each rising from the Arctic sea and each with its own character — from wide, rolling powder fields ideal for confident intermediates to steep, committing couloirs for experts. Spreading the flying across eleven zones is what lets the guides always find the best snow and safest aspect on any given day: if wind has stripped one zone or the sun has baked another, there is always fresh, sheltered terrain within a short flight of Siglufjörður. Whichever <a href="/packages">package</a> you choose, your week is flown across this home terrain, and no two days visit the same lines. It is this density and variety of accessible zones — all within minutes of a four-star base — that makes the region so productive, and so reliable across a full week.</p>

    <h2 id="month">Month by month: March, April, May and June</h2>
    <p><strong>March</strong> is deep winter in the Arctic: the coldest, most reliable powder of the season, short enough nights to still catch the Northern Lights, and a quiet, wild feel to the mountains. <strong>April</strong> is a sweet spot — still plenty of powder up high, lengthening days, and the first spring snow beginning to appear on sunny aspects. <strong>May</strong> shifts firmly into spring: long days, the arrival of dependable corn snow, and mild, pleasant skiing conditions that many guests love. <strong>June</strong> is late-season magic — the midnight sun barely dips below the horizon, corn skiing is at its most reliable, and you can ski and fly late into a bright Arctic evening. There is no single best month; there is a best month for the experience you want, and we will help you match your dates to it.</p>

    <h2 id="included">What's included, and what costs extra</h2>
    <p>An Iceland heliski <a href="/packages">package</a> is close to all-inclusive. The price covers your guaranteed vertical feet of heliskiing, IFMGA-certified mountain guiding, helicopter access flown by SENNAIR pilots, K2 freeride skis or a snowboard, the full BCA avalanche safety kit, and accommodation at Sigló Hótel with breakfast, mountain lunches and three-course dinners. What typically sits outside the package: international flights to Iceland, travel insurance, any additional vertical feet you choose to buy when conditions are exceptional, alcoholic drinks, spa treatments, and personal extras. There are no hidden surprises — because trips are sold by guaranteed vertical rather than flight time, you know exactly what your skiing entitlement is before you arrive.</p>

    <h2 id="combine">Combining heliskiing with the rest of Iceland</h2>
    <p>Many guests build their heliski week into a longer Iceland trip, and it combines beautifully. Most travellers arrive through Reykjavík, which makes it easy to add a few days exploring the south before or after skiing: the Golden Circle (Þingvellir, Geysir and Gullfoss), the geothermal Blue Lagoon, the black-sand beaches of the south coast, and — in the darker early-season weeks — dedicated Northern Lights tours. From Reykjavík it is a short domestic flight or a scenic drive north to Akureyri and on to Siglufjörður. Pairing the wild north-coast heliskiing with the classic sights of the south makes for one of the most complete adventure trips in the world. Our <a href="/travel-here">Travel Here</a> page covers the routes in detail.</p>

    <h2 id="groups">Heliskiing for groups, families and companies</h2>
    <p>Iceland heliskiing works as well for a group as for an individual. Friends travelling together, families with capable teenage skiers, and companies rewarding their teams all suit a <a href="/private-heliskiing">private helicopter</a> booking, where the group has exclusive use of the aircraft and the guides tailor the terrain and pace to the group's ability. Private weeks give you privacy, flexibility and a shared experience that becomes the trip everyone talks about for years. For smaller groups or solo travellers, the shared model pairs you with others of similar ability. Under-18s are welcome with signed parental consent. Tell us your group size and mix of abilities and we will recommend the format that gives everyone the best week.</p>

    <h2 id="helicopter">The helicopter: the AS-350 B3 (Airbus H125)</h2>
    <p>Icelandic heliskiing is flown in the AS-350 B3, now known as the Airbus H125 — the workhorse of mountain aviation worldwide and the same machine used for high-altitude rescue and the highest helicopter landings on earth. It is prized for its power, reliability and performance in thin, cold air and at altitude, which makes it ideal for Arctic mountain flying. The aircraft carries a small group of skiers plus the guide, lands lightly on summits and ridges, and repositions quickly between runs. Pilots are provided by SENNAIR — experienced, Arctic-trained professionals whose sole focus is safety, smoothness and getting you to the best snow. For most guests the flying itself becomes one of the highlights of the week.</p>

    <h2 id="avalanche">Avalanche safety, explained</h2>
    <p>Avalanches are the principal hazard in all backcountry skiing, and managing them is the central discipline of professional heliski guiding. Every day begins with the guides assessing the snowpack, the overnight weather, temperature and wind, and recent avalanche activity, then choosing terrain and aspects that match the day's conditions — this is why routes change constantly and why the guide's decisions are final. Every guest is equipped with a full BCA avalanche safety kit: a transceiver (beacon) that both transmits your location and lets you search for others, a probe to pinpoint a buried person, a shovel to dig, and an airbag pack that inflates to help keep a caught skier near the surface. Before you ski, you receive a complete briefing and, where useful, a practical transceiver drill. No system removes all risk from mountain sport — but Icelandic heliskiing is operated to the most rigorous avalanche-safety standards in the industry, led by IFMGA-certified guides.</p>

    <h2 id="beyond-skiing">Non-skiing partners and life in Siglufjörður</h2>
    <p>A heliski trip is not only for those in the helicopter. Siglufjörður is a charming, historic herring town with plenty to fill a non-skiing partner's day: the award-winning Herring Era Museum, harbour cafés and restaurants, coastal and valley walks, the geothermal hot tubs and spa at <a href="/siglo-hotel">Sigló Hótel</a>, and — in season — whale-watching and Northern Lights from the water's edge. Because the hotel sits on the marina at the foot of the terrain, skiers and non-skiers share the same beautiful base and reunite each evening over dinner. It makes Iceland one of the easiest heliski destinations to bring a partner who does not ski.</p>

    <h2 id="food">Food and dining on a heliski week</h2>
    <p>Meals are part of the experience, not an afterthought. Days begin with a generous breakfast buffet at Sigló Hótel, mountain lunches are taken in the field between runs, and evenings end with three-course dinners at the hotel's Sunna restaurant, which draws on fresh Icelandic seafood, lamb and local produce. After a big day skiing, dinner on the harbour — often with the light still in the sky in late season — is one of the quiet pleasures of a trip here. Dietary requirements are easily accommodated; let us know when you book.</p>

    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <div class="gd-faq">
      <details><summary>Is heliskiing in Iceland worth it?</summary><p>For anyone comfortable off-piste, yes — untouched Arctic powder, up to 25,000 vertical feet a day, rare sea-to-summit descents, the midnight sun and Northern Lights, and a four-star base make it one of the most complete heliski experiences anywhere.</p></details>
      <details><summary>How much does heliskiing in Iceland cost?</summary><p>Packages run from around €3,490 for a shorter shared week up to €82,990 for a fully private helicopter week, priced by guaranteed vertical feet and including guiding, the helicopter, gear, avalanche equipment and accommodation with meals at Sigló Hótel. See the <a href="/packages">packages</a> for current pricing.</p></details>
      <details><summary>When is the best time to heliski in Iceland?</summary><p>March to mid-June. March–April for powder and the Northern Lights; May–June for reliable spring corn snow under the midnight sun.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Is heliskiing dangerous?</summary><p>It carries real backcountry risk, principally avalanches, managed to the highest standard by IFMGA-certified guides, full avalanche safety equipment, and experienced Arctic pilots. Some inherent risk always remains in mountain sport.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Can beginners go heliskiing?</summary><p>It suits strong intermediate to advanced skiers and riders comfortable off-piste for a full day, rather than absolute beginners. Guides match terrain to the group, and the late-season corn window is the gentlest introduction.</p></details>
      <details><summary>How does Iceland compare to Canada or Alaska?</summary><p>Iceland's signature is sea-to-summit terrain and Arctic light, with a compact four-star base. Canada offers deep tree skiing, Alaska the steepest lines, Japan the lightest snow — Iceland is the most accessible and civilised of the four.</p></details>
    </div>

    <h2 id="book">How to book — and why through an authorised agent</h2>
    <p>Heliski Travel is the authorised booking agent for Viking Heliskiing on the Troll Peninsula. Booking through an agent costs you no more than booking direct, and gives you a single relationship handling every detail — dates, group size, private or shared flights, hotel, transfers and the small things that make a trip run smoothly. From your first message to the helicopter, one team looks after everything, with a reply within 12 hours.</p>
    <p>The best next step is simply to tell us your dates and group size. Read more about the region on our <a href="/iceland">Iceland guide</a>, browse the <a href="/packages">packages</a>, or <a href="/contact">get in touch</a> for a tailored quote.</p>

